[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":955},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F11\u002F18\u002Fjavascript-core-36-functions-this-iife\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F11\u002F18\u002Fjavascript-core-36-functions-this-iife\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F11\u002F18\u002Fjavascript-core-36-functions-this-iife\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F11\u002F18\u002Fjavascript-core-36-functions-this-iife\u002F":930,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F11\u002F18\u002Fjavascript-core-36-functions-this-iife\u002F":939},"\u002Fjavascript\u002F20201118\u002F707576253\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":913,"date":914,"description":915,"extension":916,"lang":917,"meta":918,"navigation":84,"path":919,"readingMinutes":920,"seo":921,"standalone":922,"stem":923,"tags":924,"tldr":927,"updated":914,"url":928,"__hash__":929},"content\u002Fen\u002FJavaScript\u002Fjavascript-core-36-functions-this-iife.md","JavaScript Core Concepts (36): Functions & This — The IIFE","1000910688",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":908},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,27,95,98,128,135,195,198,244,247,278,281,284,360,371,377,380,385,397,463,473,555,563,603,610,675,686,752,758,824,832,838,875,878,889,893,904],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"The IIFE is one of those tricks you see absolutely everywhere — in libraries, in frameworks, in legacy code. So it's worth knowing what it actually is.",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"the-iife","The IIFE",[17,25,26],{},"So what's an IIFE? The full name is \"immediately-invoked function expression\" — IIFE for short. In the last chapter we saw that a named function declaration only runs when you actually call it.",[28,29,34],"pre",{"className":30,"code":31,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","function fn() {\n  console.log('Ray');\n}\n\nfn();\n","js","",[35,36,37,54,73,79,86],"code",{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,39,42,46,50],"span",{"class":40,"line":41},"line",1,[38,43,45],{"class":44},"sWyjQ","function",[38,47,49],{"class":48},"sj_SG"," fn",[38,51,53],{"class":52},"sMAXC","() {\n",[38,55,57,60,63,66,70],{"class":40,"line":56},2,[38,58,59],{"class":52},"  console.",[38,61,62],{"class":48},"log",[38,64,65],{"class":52},"(",[38,67,69],{"class":68},"sTRMh","'Ray'",[38,71,72],{"class":52},");\n",[38,74,76],{"class":40,"line":75},3,[38,77,78],{"class":52},"}\n",[38,80,82],{"class":40,"line":81},4,[38,83,85],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":84},true,"\n",[38,87,89,92],{"class":40,"line":88},5,[38,90,91],{"class":48},"fn",[38,93,94],{"class":52},"();\n",[17,96,97],{},"An IIFE doesn't wait for you to call it. The moment the code runs, it runs itself.",[28,99,101],{"className":30,"code":100,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"(function() {\n  console.log('Ray');\n})();\n",[35,102,103,111,123],{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,104,105,107,109],{"class":40,"line":41},[38,106,65],{"class":52},[38,108,45],{"class":44},[38,110,53],{"class":52},[38,112,113,115,117,119,121],{"class":40,"line":56},[38,114,59],{"class":52},[38,116,62],{"class":48},[38,118,65],{"class":52},[38,120,69],{"class":68},[38,122,72],{"class":52},[38,124,125],{"class":40,"line":75},[38,126,127],{"class":52},"})();\n",[17,129,130,131,134],{},"The key to an IIFE is that pair of parens ",[35,132,133],{},"()"," at the very end. You'll usually see it written one of two ways:",[28,136,138],{"className":30,"code":137,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"(function() {\n  console.log('Ray');\n})();\n\n(function() {\n  console.log('Ray');\n}());\n",[35,139,140,148,160,164,168,176,189],{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,141,142,144,146],{"class":40,"line":41},[38,143,65],{"class":52},[38,145,45],{"class":44},[38,147,53],{"class":52},[38,149,150,152,154,156,158],{"class":40,"line":56},[38,151,59],{"class":52},[38,153,62],{"class":48},[38,155,65],{"class":52},[38,157,69],{"class":68},[38,159,72],{"class":52},[38,161,162],{"class":40,"line":75},[38,163,127],{"class":52},[38,165,166],{"class":40,"line":81},[38,167,85],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":84},[38,169,170,172,174],{"class":40,"line":88},[38,171,65],{"class":52},[38,173,45],{"class":44},[38,175,53],{"class":52},[38,177,179,181,183,185,187],{"class":40,"line":178},6,[38,180,59],{"class":52},[38,182,62],{"class":48},[38,184,65],{"class":52},[38,186,69],{"class":68},[38,188,72],{"class":52},[38,190,192],{"class":40,"line":191},7,[38,193,194],{"class":52},"}());\n",[17,196,197],{},"There's no right answer between these two — both run the IIFE just fine. Notice the IIFE has no name, so it's a kind of anonymous function. But it's different from the anonymous function expressions we saw earlier — a regular anonymous expression has to be called before its body runs.",[28,199,201],{"className":30,"code":200,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"var fn = function() {\n  console.log('Ray');\n}\n\nfn();\n",[35,202,203,218,230,234,238],{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,204,205,208,210,213,216],{"class":40,"line":41},[38,206,207],{"class":44},"var",[38,209,49],{"class":48},[38,211,212],{"class":44}," =",[38,214,215],{"class":44}," function",[38,217,53],{"class":52},[38,219,220,222,224,226,228],{"class":40,"line":56},[38,221,59],{"class":52},[38,223,62],{"class":48},[38,225,65],{"class":52},[38,227,69],{"class":68},[38,229,72],{"class":52},[38,231,232],{"class":40,"line":75},[38,233,78],{"class":52},[38,235,236],{"class":40,"line":81},[38,237,85],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":84},[38,239,240,242],{"class":40,"line":88},[38,241,91],{"class":48},[38,243,94],{"class":52},[17,245,246],{},"Now someone might wonder — what counts as this?",[28,248,250],{"className":30,"code":249,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"(function fn() {\n  console.log('Ray');\n}());\n",[35,251,252,262,274],{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,253,254,256,258,260],{"class":40,"line":41},[38,255,65],{"class":52},[38,257,45],{"class":44},[38,259,49],{"class":48},[38,261,53],{"class":52},[38,263,264,266,268,270,272],{"class":40,"line":56},[38,265,59],{"class":52},[38,267,62],{"class":48},[38,269,65],{"class":52},[38,271,69],{"class":68},[38,273,72],{"class":52},[38,275,276],{"class":40,"line":75},[38,277,194],{"class":52},[17,279,280],{},"That's also an IIFE. The function name isn't actually needed here — there's no point to it — but JavaScript won't warn you that you can drop it.",[17,282,283],{},"So the first feature of an IIFE is pretty obvious: it runs immediately (well, duh). But there's another one. Once an IIFE finishes, you can't call it again — not from outside, not at all — and any variables declared inside it are only accessible within the IIFE.",[28,285,287],{"className":30,"code":286,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"(function fn() {\n  console.log('Ray');\n  var a = 'Hello';\n}());\n\nfn(); \u002F\u002F fn is not defined\nconsole.log(a); \u002F\u002F a is not defined\n",[35,288,289,299,311,328,332,336,347],{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,290,291,293,295,297],{"class":40,"line":41},[38,292,65],{"class":52},[38,294,45],{"class":44},[38,296,49],{"class":48},[38,298,53],{"class":52},[38,300,301,303,305,307,309],{"class":40,"line":56},[38,302,59],{"class":52},[38,304,62],{"class":48},[38,306,65],{"class":52},[38,308,69],{"class":68},[38,310,72],{"class":52},[38,312,313,316,319,322,325],{"class":40,"line":75},[38,314,315],{"class":44},"  var",[38,317,318],{"class":52}," a ",[38,320,321],{"class":44},"=",[38,323,324],{"class":68}," 'Hello'",[38,326,327],{"class":52},";\n",[38,329,330],{"class":40,"line":81},[38,331,194],{"class":52},[38,333,334],{"class":40,"line":88},[38,335,85],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":84},[38,337,338,340,343],{"class":40,"line":178},[38,339,91],{"class":48},[38,341,342],{"class":52},"(); ",[38,344,346],{"class":345},"sQrFR","\u002F\u002F fn is not defined\n",[38,348,349,352,354,357],{"class":40,"line":191},[38,350,351],{"class":52},"console.",[38,353,62],{"class":48},[38,355,356],{"class":52},"(a); ",[38,358,359],{"class":345},"\u002F\u002F a is not defined\n",[17,361,362,363,370],{},"Let's look at MDN's description of the ",[364,365,369],"a",{"href":366,"rel":367},"https:\u002F\u002Fdeveloper.mozilla.org\u002Fen-US\u002Fdocs\u002FGlossary\u002FIIFE",[368],"nofollow","IIFE",":",[372,373,374],"blockquote",{},[17,375,376],{},"An IIFE (Immediately Invoked Function Expression) is a JavaScript function that runs as soon as it is defined.",[17,378,379],{},"There's another important point worth noting here:",[372,381,382],{},[17,383,384],{},"This pattern keeps the variables inside from polluting the global scope.",[17,386,387,388,390,391,393,394,370],{},"What does that mean? The whole point of an IIFE comes down to understanding scope. Before block scope existed — before ES6, basically — pollution was really easy to cause, because ",[35,389,207],{}," is scoped to the nearest ",[35,392,45],{},", not the nearest block. So code like this leaks straight into ",[35,395,396],{},"window",[28,398,400],{"className":30,"code":399,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"for(var i = 0; i \u003C 10; i++) {\n  console.log(i);\n}\nconsole.log(i); \u002F\u002F 10\n",[35,401,402,438,447,451],{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,403,404,407,409,411,414,416,420,423,426,429,432,435],{"class":40,"line":41},[38,405,406],{"class":44},"for",[38,408,65],{"class":52},[38,410,207],{"class":44},[38,412,413],{"class":52}," i ",[38,415,321],{"class":44},[38,417,419],{"class":418},"sCcAr"," 0",[38,421,422],{"class":52},"; i ",[38,424,425],{"class":44},"\u003C",[38,427,428],{"class":418}," 10",[38,430,431],{"class":52},"; i",[38,433,434],{"class":44},"++",[38,436,437],{"class":52},") {\n",[38,439,440,442,444],{"class":40,"line":56},[38,441,59],{"class":52},[38,443,62],{"class":48},[38,445,446],{"class":52},"(i);\n",[38,448,449],{"class":40,"line":75},[38,450,78],{"class":52},[38,452,453,455,457,460],{"class":40,"line":81},[38,454,351],{"class":52},[38,456,62],{"class":48},[38,458,459],{"class":52},"(i); ",[38,461,462],{"class":345},"\u002F\u002F 10\n",[17,464,465,466,468,469,472],{},"We want to avoid polluting ",[35,467,396],{}," while we're developing. This is exactly where an IIFE helps — it boxes in the scope so the variable ",[35,470,471],{},"i"," only lives inside the IIFE.",[28,474,476],{"className":30,"code":475,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"(function() {\n  for(var i = 0; i \u003C 10; i++) {\n    console.log(i); \u002F\u002F 0~9\n  }\n  console.log(i); \u002F\u002F 10\n})();\nconsole.log(i); \u002F\u002F i is not defined\n",[35,477,478,486,513,525,530,540,544],{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,479,480,482,484],{"class":40,"line":41},[38,481,65],{"class":52},[38,483,45],{"class":44},[38,485,53],{"class":52},[38,487,488,491,493,495,497,499,501,503,505,507,509,511],{"class":40,"line":56},[38,489,490],{"class":44},"  for",[38,492,65],{"class":52},[38,494,207],{"class":44},[38,496,413],{"class":52},[38,498,321],{"class":44},[38,500,419],{"class":418},[38,502,422],{"class":52},[38,504,425],{"class":44},[38,506,428],{"class":418},[38,508,431],{"class":52},[38,510,434],{"class":44},[38,512,437],{"class":52},[38,514,515,518,520,522],{"class":40,"line":75},[38,516,517],{"class":52},"    console.",[38,519,62],{"class":48},[38,521,459],{"class":52},[38,523,524],{"class":345},"\u002F\u002F 0~9\n",[38,526,527],{"class":40,"line":81},[38,528,529],{"class":52},"  }\n",[38,531,532,534,536,538],{"class":40,"line":88},[38,533,59],{"class":52},[38,535,62],{"class":48},[38,537,459],{"class":52},[38,539,462],{"class":345},[38,541,542],{"class":40,"line":178},[38,543,127],{"class":52},[38,545,546,548,550,552],{"class":40,"line":191},[38,547,351],{"class":52},[38,549,62],{"class":48},[38,551,459],{"class":52},[38,553,554],{"class":345},"\u002F\u002F i is not defined\n",[17,556,557,558,562],{},"Now you might ask — if the outside can't get at the IIFE's internal variables and functions, can we at least pass arguments ",[559,560,561],"em",{},"in","? Yep, we can. Here's how:",[28,564,566],{"className":30,"code":565,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"(function(name) {\n  console.log(name); \u002F\u002F Ray\n})('Ray');\n",[35,567,568,582,594],{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,569,570,572,574,576,580],{"class":40,"line":41},[38,571,65],{"class":52},[38,573,45],{"class":44},[38,575,65],{"class":52},[38,577,579],{"class":578},"s_sBn","name",[38,581,437],{"class":52},[38,583,584,586,588,591],{"class":40,"line":56},[38,585,59],{"class":52},[38,587,62],{"class":48},[38,589,590],{"class":52},"(name); ",[38,592,593],{"class":345},"\u002F\u002F Ray\n",[38,595,596,599,601],{"class":40,"line":75},[38,597,598],{"class":52},"})(",[38,600,69],{"class":68},[38,602,72],{"class":52},[17,604,605,606,609],{},"And since an IIFE is itself an expression, you can ",[35,607,608],{},"return"," a value from it and catch it with a variable:",[28,611,613],{"className":30,"code":612,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"var name = (function(name) {\n  console.log(name); \u002F\u002F Ray\n  return name;\n})('Ray');\n\nconsole.log(name); \u002F\u002F Ray\n",[35,614,615,635,645,653,661,665],{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,616,617,619,622,624,627,629,631,633],{"class":40,"line":41},[38,618,207],{"class":44},[38,620,621],{"class":52}," name ",[38,623,321],{"class":44},[38,625,626],{"class":52}," (",[38,628,45],{"class":44},[38,630,65],{"class":52},[38,632,579],{"class":578},[38,634,437],{"class":52},[38,636,637,639,641,643],{"class":40,"line":56},[38,638,59],{"class":52},[38,640,62],{"class":48},[38,642,590],{"class":52},[38,644,593],{"class":345},[38,646,647,650],{"class":40,"line":75},[38,648,649],{"class":44},"  return",[38,651,652],{"class":52}," name;\n",[38,654,655,657,659],{"class":40,"line":81},[38,656,598],{"class":52},[38,658,69],{"class":68},[38,660,72],{"class":52},[38,662,663],{"class":40,"line":88},[38,664,85],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":84},[38,666,667,669,671,673],{"class":40,"line":178},[38,668,351],{"class":52},[38,670,62],{"class":48},[38,672,590],{"class":52},[38,674,593],{"class":345},[17,676,677,678,681,682,685],{},"Finally, there's one classic IIFE landmine — the ",[35,679,680],{},";",". If you don't write your semicolons correctly, you'll hit this error: ",[35,683,684],{},"Uncaught TypeError: (intermediate value)(...) is not a function",".",[28,687,689],{"className":30,"code":688,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"(function(name) {\n  console.log(name); \u002F\u002F Ray\n})('Ray')\n(function(name) {\n  console.log(name); \u002F\u002F Ray\n})('Ray')\n",[35,690,691,703,713,722,734,744],{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,692,693,695,697,699,701],{"class":40,"line":41},[38,694,65],{"class":52},[38,696,45],{"class":44},[38,698,65],{"class":52},[38,700,579],{"class":578},[38,702,437],{"class":52},[38,704,705,707,709,711],{"class":40,"line":56},[38,706,59],{"class":52},[38,708,62],{"class":48},[38,710,590],{"class":52},[38,712,593],{"class":345},[38,714,715,717,719],{"class":40,"line":75},[38,716,598],{"class":52},[38,718,69],{"class":68},[38,720,721],{"class":52},")\n",[38,723,724,726,728,730,732],{"class":40,"line":81},[38,725,65],{"class":52},[38,727,45],{"class":44},[38,729,65],{"class":52},[38,731,579],{"class":578},[38,733,437],{"class":52},[38,735,736,738,740,742],{"class":40,"line":88},[38,737,59],{"class":52},[38,739,62],{"class":48},[38,741,590],{"class":52},[38,743,593],{"class":345},[38,745,746,748,750],{"class":40,"line":178},[38,747,598],{"class":52},[38,749,69],{"class":68},[38,751,721],{"class":52},[17,753,754,755,757],{},"The fix is just to add a ",[35,756,680],{}," in front of the opening paren:",[28,759,761],{"className":30,"code":760,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"(function(name) {\n  console.log(name); \u002F\u002F Ray\n})('Ray')\n;(function(name) {\n  console.log(name); \u002F\u002F Ray\n})('Ray')\n",[35,762,763,775,785,793,806,816],{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,764,765,767,769,771,773],{"class":40,"line":41},[38,766,65],{"class":52},[38,768,45],{"class":44},[38,770,65],{"class":52},[38,772,579],{"class":578},[38,774,437],{"class":52},[38,776,777,779,781,783],{"class":40,"line":56},[38,778,59],{"class":52},[38,780,62],{"class":48},[38,782,590],{"class":52},[38,784,593],{"class":345},[38,786,787,789,791],{"class":40,"line":75},[38,788,598],{"class":52},[38,790,69],{"class":68},[38,792,721],{"class":52},[38,794,795,798,800,802,804],{"class":40,"line":81},[38,796,797],{"class":52},";(",[38,799,45],{"class":44},[38,801,65],{"class":52},[38,803,579],{"class":578},[38,805,437],{"class":52},[38,807,808,810,812,814],{"class":40,"line":88},[38,809,59],{"class":52},[38,811,62],{"class":48},[38,813,590],{"class":52},[38,815,593],{"class":345},[38,817,818,820,822],{"class":40,"line":178},[38,819,598],{"class":52},[38,821,69],{"class":68},[38,823,721],{"class":52},[17,825,826,827,831],{},"The root cause here ties back to a much earlier chapter — \"",[364,828,830],{"href":829},"\u002Fjavascript\u002F20200613\u002F3587770435","JavaScript Core Concepts (12): Operators, Types & Grammar — ASI Automatic Semicolon Insertion"," (article in Mandarin)\".",[17,833,834,835,837],{},"So to wrap up — why use an IIFE at all? The main goal is to avoid polluting the global execution context and causing collisions. In the example below, even though the variable lives inside the function, the ",[35,836,45],{}," itself is declared directly in the global execution context:",[28,839,841],{"className":30,"code":840,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"function getName() {\n  console.log('Ray');\n}\ngetName();\n",[35,842,843,852,864,868],{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,844,845,847,850],{"class":40,"line":41},[38,846,45],{"class":44},[38,848,849],{"class":48}," getName",[38,851,53],{"class":52},[38,853,854,856,858,860,862],{"class":40,"line":56},[38,855,59],{"class":52},[38,857,62],{"class":48},[38,859,65],{"class":52},[38,861,69],{"class":68},[38,863,72],{"class":52},[38,865,866],{"class":40,"line":75},[38,867,78],{"class":52},[38,869,870,873],{"class":40,"line":81},[38,871,872],{"class":48},"getName",[38,874,94],{"class":52},[17,876,877],{},"So if there's another variable or function with a similar name floating